4</Rating>
<text>As a Salvadoran-American I grew up on Salvadoran food, I have to say that this is by far the best chicharon pupusas I've had outside my mom's house. On my first visit I order the pan en gallina (roughly translated; chicken on french bread) this was a masterpiece, had the Salvadoran vinegar veggie mix, avocado, slaw and the chicken cooked in a stew... I think it is a stew... its definately not a soup. The only downside of this "sandwich" was the soggyness of the bottom of the bread from adding too much stew over it. If you order this item, I recommend trying each item individually before eating it all together. Although delicious in my opinion. I also tested the pupusas, the chicharon checks out, but if you order it mixed with cheese, the cheese may overwhelm the taste of the chicharon. Of course cheese pupusas are always good.

P.s. before you receive your food, you recieve and cut up hand tossed fried tortilla with a refried bean dip.... this by so far is the closest item that I am accustomed too and fell in love with the memories and taste of the refried beans.< /text><pictures>None< /pictures><Resp>None<//Resp>< gmap_id>

< Text>
Despite all the reviews, I decided to take a look at Summer House after unsuccessful attempts in finding affordable rentals in surrounding neighborhoods. I had lived in Alameda before AND took a look at Summer House 3 years prior. Now, I'm a resident here. I have to say that the new management has changed this place for the better. Now that construction is complete, the grounds are gorgeous with water fountains all around, a gigantic swimming pool and beautiful plants and flowers.  The groundskeepers should be given full credit, as I see them outside everyday working on keeping the place clean and attractive (*reviews have been given about the trash and furniture around the dumpsters, which is accurate still, however, this is at the fault of the residents, not the property managers). The ordinary apartments are comparable to their going rates, so if you are looking for something plain to get you through the year, this is a great spot. They come with a double sink, dishwasher, electric stove, microwave, carpeted rooms, and easy cable hookup. So far we've had to call maintenance twice in the 3 months that we've been here. Though some appliances were not working properly when we moved in, the maintenance people were there on time and fixed our problems right away... no questions asked. Be careful for the "water fee" which is divided among the complex as a whole and attached to your monthly rent. There is ample parking but the car gates are not secure. Plenty of kids here who play in the complex when school is out. We live with a 10 year-old so he made friends right away. Last note, it can get a little noisy since the walls are pretty thin. I would suggest sticking with a top floor.<//Text>

< Review>
Summer house apartments are a great option if you're moving into the bay. When I moved into Alameda 2 years ago I found their prices to be competitive and even though they raised my rent it's still below market value. They're dog friendly, pretty responsive, and the units themselves are on the nicer side. Everyone in my building is pretty chill and I haven't heard about any noise problems.
Cons:
- Not everyone is good with their own dog and I've seen several incidents where on-leash dogs were being really aggressive with other dogs (not the apartment's fault but it's still something to be aware of).
- We've had a few minor annoyances with maintenance but we don't call them very often.
- Sometimes non-residents will get into the habit of letting themselves into the complex. Nothing dangerous though. Example: For a few weeks a guy would use a stick every day to let himself into one of the parking lot areas and just make calls all day in front of my building. I guess it wouldn't have been an issue if he wasn't glaring at all of the residents that walked by.< /Review>

<Gmap_id>0x808f80df1c7d8be3:0x9029d8150390492</Gmap_id><userid>107265274637859422193< /userid><username>Jeff Scott<//username><Date>1402780195982<//Date>< Review>
It was a bad omen when I went to the bank for a cashier's check for rent and deposit, and the teller told me I should tear it up find a new place if I hadn't signed anything yet.  These have been my negative experiences in the one year I have lived here:

1. My roommate and I voiced concern over parking on the tour.  Our guide said, "The 3 bedroom apartments come with 2 spaces."  This is an outright lie. The excuse: "Oh, sorry, he is new here."

2. We were told the prices of the apartments are all reflected on the website.  We applied for our apartment based on website listing, and then the contract was for $200 more per month.  Their excuse was, "Sometimes there's a significant delay between the website updates and actual rent changes, especially during the summer when there are a lot of moves."

3. After signing a lease for $200 more than expected and one fewer parking space, a new blank lease appeared in our email  a month later asking for even more money.  They said there was an error, and we weren't being charged enough.  They didn't push it after we pointed out this was blatantly illegal, but they still act like they're doing us a huge favor and we're just trying to scheme them out of cash.

4. There is a significant amount of noise at night.  I was particularly peeved one night when a car with a custom engine and very loud after stock muffler was parked below my window at 1:30 AM just revving the engine over and over again.  Then the guy left the doors open on both sides and BLASTED his stereo.  I was going to call security, but when I looked again, I saw that it was the security guard.  I had to be at work 5 hours later.

5. Management is in cahoots with some local towing company, and they call them immediately if anything is amiss.  If you need to unload groceries because you don't have enough parking spots that come with the apartment, you're gambling if it will be there when you return, even if it's only 10 min.

6. People like to dig through the dumpster below my bedroom window on a daily basis, and they can be rather loud at times, too.

7. There are loud children everywhere.  Make sure your apartment isn't next to the parking lot or the playground.

8. You are next to 2 schools, which is convenient if you have kids, but a pain around 8AM and 3PM.

9. There's a creepy old guy in the complex across the street who just walks up and down the sidewalk and calls police for people who are parked illegally, even if you tell him you just need to run a bag of groceries upstairs before you hunt for parking elsewhere.

Basically, I should have listened to my bank teller.  I'm moving in a week, and I can't wait.<//Review>

I really liked living here. Here are the pros and cons:
Pros:
- Management office: People in the management office are very nice and helpful. I did not deal with all of them (they look very nice though), but I usually talk to Britnie, she is very very nice girl and very helpful. Always optimistic :)
- Price: Apartment price was very nice especially if u work in SF, though they require very good credit, and relatively high income to be able to live there
- Maintenance: They respond very quickly, usually less than 24 hours
- Facilities: Swimming pool, Gym, playground for kids, barbecue area
- Security: Place has gates and security guards at night.
- unit: has microwave and dishwasher
- Commute: bus station is 5 mins walk. 25 minutes Bus to SF, 5 mins to Oakland.

Cons:
- Washers are very good, but dryers were not that great. However, I knew that they will have pretty new washers/dryers on January 2016
- Sometimes, you hear people's footsteps above you, but its okay for me.
- Carpet in my apartment was not that new.<//text>

< review>
I drive for Uber and Lyft part time and needed to get an annual inspection done. I called Pep Boys in San Marcos to see if I needed to schedule an appointment and was greeted by Robert on the phone. He was pleasant and told me to come on in whenever and it shouldn't take it too long.

I drove over and was surprised there was no line whatsoever so it turned out great. I was greeted first by Robert, the same person that had assisted me over the phone. He said that he could do the inspection now and it would take about 15 minutes to complete and he'd fill out both forms for Uber and Lyft. I waited in the waiting area which had a Keurig machine for free coffee which was nice. About 10 minutes later, he was all done and I paid and was on my way.

I would definitely visit this Pep Boys again. Super simple, straight forward, no wait, friendly, fast, and helpful. Also, this location doesn't have the same layout as a regular Pep Boys. No car parts. Mostly service and tires it seems. Almost has a small business type feel.< /review>

<time>1518492376707<//time><rate>5</rate>< review>
Consistently serving cheap and fresh tasting hamburgers. Some of my favorite french fries, which can be made even better by adding melted cheese or having them made "Animal Style". A wonderful selection of soft drinks and classic tasting milkshakes, In-N-Out makes shame of the old fashioned rule that things cant be quick, cheap, and good tasting all at the same time. For Californians and people who have frequented the West Coast, this should feel nostalgic. For anyone who hasn't had the chance to taste it, In-N-Out will undoubtedly remain the one of the highlights of their trip to the Bay Area.<//review>

<Review>A tremendous nightmare starting with the parking and lack of empathy for covid-19. This particular location does not care about covid-19 cases or if you get sick or not. With a rush to open their doors so quickly, it's no wonder people are flocking to this place like the plague. I've seen people go in (only once & final time) without a mask and come out coughing and panting. If that's the case, they might as well let the whole city of Tracy in and avoid the rules altogether, making it impossible for you to get into the hospital if you need to. Although they have signs on the doors, people are still being let in maskless, crowded lines and less cleaning. The parking lot intrudes on the smaller businesses around it, meaning you can't park anywhere to get to those small shops, you have to park across the street. It was also closed briefly during the pandemic to sanitize the entire store in which didn't help but only for a few days. But like all places, if someone has tested positive for covid-19, that person may or may not wish to disclose that information with the company, in great fear of losing their job. Not much they can do about it, but if you're worried about contracting the virus, you may want to opt out of fast food for awhile and this place is no exception. The lines are ridiculously long and the customers are impatient, rude and negligent. Good luck waiting an hour in the drive thru.
